T1  - Losing Control? The Two-Decade Decline in Loan Covenant Violations
AU  - GRIFFIN, THOMAS P.
AU  - NINI, GREG
AU  - SMITH, DAVID C.
Y1  - 2026/02/01
PY  - 2026
DA  - 2026/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.70005
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - J Finance
SP  - 371
EP  - 412
VL  - 81
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.70005
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT The annual proportion of U.S. public firms that reported a financial covenant violation fell roughly 70% between 1997 and 2019. To understand this trend, we develop an estimable model of covenant design that depends on the ability to differentiate between distressed and nondistressed borrowers and the relative costs associated with screening incorrectly. We find that the drop in violations is best explained by an increased willingness to forgo early detection of distressed borrowers in exchange for fewer inconsequential violations, which we attribute largely to a shift in the composition of public borrowers and partly to heightened investor sentiment during the 2010s.
ER  - 

